text.text: A Guide to Clapham

What's the haps in the Claps? Almost more than we can fit in, actually. Home of Vivienne Westwood, scene of SW4, the wonder that is Infernos...ok, scratch that last one. Seriously though, this little pocket of South London has more going on than we know what to do with. It's not got the most flattering rep for its abundance of yuppies but let's dispense with reputation and say it how we see it.
Best for... tea and French pastries

tip.text:
Nipping across the Channel for a French cafe experience is a bit of a schlep, so we'll just stick to Madeleine's in Clapham. You may not see him, but in the kitchen there's a pastry chef from France, firing out the best cakes and pastries all day - including gluten-free goodies. If you give him a couple of days notice, he can even custom bake you cakes for any occasion. Total gent.

There's fresh onion soup every day (obviously), and different daily special stews. The coffee here is good, but the teas are the MVP – all lined up on the counter in glass jars. Blackcurrant hibiscus, flowering osmanthus... whatever you fancy.

tip.text:
Mama Lan is the tiny, ramshackle wonder we love coming back to. There's only room for a few tables, but their selection of incredible dumplings, noodle soups, and a cheeky chicken wing or two on the side is a simple formula which they've perfected.

There are only one or two beers to choose from, and a few wines, but that's all you need. Go for one of their exotic teas, or a flowery mocktail to finish things off with.

tip.text:
This is like the Variety Pack of pubs – there's a stage downstairs by the bar for live music, a huge room in the back for live comedy, and upstairs is a dedicated theatre. We would say it's hard to choose what to see, but the bands only start playing after the theatre wraps up, so you can double up on your culture without having to put down your pint.

Definitely come down for the blues jams they put on – anyone can put their name down, get up on stage and noodle away. Plus the first Saturday of the month is Northern Soul vinyl night – the place goes mental for that.

tip.text:
Proving you don't need to be big to pack a punch is Venn Street Market - a local community Saturday market doling out plenty of quality produce along with those obligatory community vibes. A speedy browser could get this one done in 10-15 minutes, but where's the fun in that? For there are breads, pastries, fish, meat, veggies, smoothies, chocolate and cheese to peruse.

There are also a few street food options including an increasing vegan presence. That said, the hog roast sandwich is probably the most popular thing on the market. In the summer, those with any sense grab some food from here and take it over to the Common.

tip.text:
The Dairy opened in 2013, using vegetables and herbs grown on its roof along with honey from its bees to create an exciting fine dining spot in Clapham. Next door is their 'naughty little brother', Counter Culture, which uses all the same fresh ingredients and pickling, fermenting and curing techniques to make more edgy tapas-style small plates. Every two months these guys tackle a new country's food, and put their own spin on it.

Munch on the goodies in their tiny space which seats a measly 15 (with a small standing space, if you've got the stamina). It's also BYOB (with £10 corkage), but not bookable so plan carefully and be prepared to queue.

Every two months these guys tackle a new country's food and put their own spin on it. It's a tiny, cosy space which seats 14, is unbookable and is also BYOB - which means you might have to queue for these delicious bites.
Best for... a cheap eat

tip.text:
You'll be stepping out of here a convert to the way of the roti, and planning a trip to Trinidad. This tiny takeaway joint may be simple, but for a little over a fiver you're getting some of the best spicy Caribbean chow that money can buy, plus some top level chat from the staff too. Go for the curried goat in a roti wrap with a side of pumpkin, and you'll be a happy camper.

Good luck still having room for anything else, but if you do, there's homemade coconut bread and fudge to get your sugar levels spiking.

tip.text: Located bang smack opposite Clapham underground station, this independent wine bar and shop is the perfect pit-stop for speedy commuters or those with more time to wet their whistle properly. When it comes to wine, this bunch really have it on lockdown -  their bespoke events, wine tastings, pairings and speciality in biodynamic, organic and sustainable wines are all very impressive. And if you fancy mixing things up, beers, cocktails and tasty morsels are also up for grabs.

tip.text:
The chefs serve up some cracking British game dishes here, like Terrine of Partridge with Pear and Pistachio on Toasted Brioche, or Red Deer cooked over charcoal. They even have their own signature gin, created by the Cambridge Distillery.

Upstairs, they host guest chef evenings for 20 or so lucky folk (you need to book these way in advance), where you get the full shebang – chat from the chef, exclusive wine pairings, the lot.

tip.text:
Skip a step in the drinking / going-to-the-loo circle of life and head into an actual bog for a drink. WC is a former Victorian public toilet underneath the streets of Clapham and it's really something special. They've somehow managed to keep the original features of the place including scrawled love letters on the walls, but have plushed things up with little candlelit booths making it Grade-A date material.

Wine and charcuterie (hence the WC name) is the order of the day here, and for God's sake order the Rabbit & Armagnac Salami - it's right on the money.

tip.text:
With their middle finger up at pub chains, The King & Co is an independent boozer that loves doing its own thing. The pub itself has a friendly, local vibe but the kitchen is where it’s really at. You see they host a constant stream of London’s most exciting chefs. Guest residencies usually last a couple of months and in the past have included the likes of tapas dons Donostia Social Club and BBQ bigwigs Miss P’s Barbecue.

The turnaround for beers and ciders is just as speedy. Cask Ale Club on Mondays offers all cask ales at £3.20 and their Bottomless Boozy Brunch every Saturday is where the never-ending Bloody Marys are at.

tip.text:
If you're not up for chic and sophisticated, Venn Street Records is a undeniably fun spot for some cheaper japes. It's good honest rock vibes inside, with its vintage NME pages plastered all over the walls, and the cocktails that nod towards the greats, like the AC/Daquiri. It's not just the Stella muck on the beer front either - they sell a few Brewdog choices which are always welcome.

Live music is also on here, but it can get super busy. It is just off Clapham High Street, after all.
